03:29.000 --> 03:30.351
<i>on my scale model Glee Club
diorama.</i>

03:30.435 --> 03:32.603
<i>Here we are weeks away
from graduation,</i>

03:32.671 --> 03:34.221
<i>and I've got three seniors
in trouble.</i>

03:34.306 --> 03:37.141
If Noah's Ark Pool Cleaning
Service can do 20 pools a week

03:37.192 --> 03:39.360
at 50 bucks a pop, I'm making...

03:39.444 --> 03:40.861
Do you even know how
to use a calculator?

03:40.946 --> 03:42.363
<i>WILL:
First, there's Finn.</i>

03:42.447 --> 03:44.649
<i>He's got all this talent,
but no self-esteem.</i>

03:44.700 --> 03:46.651
Which is why Finn should
come to L.A. with me.

03:46.702 --> 03:48.035
<i>And then there's Mercedes.</i>

03:48.120 --> 03:49.620
<i>She's just as talented
as Rachel and Kurt,</i>

03:49.688 --> 03:50.871
<i>but she doesn't have
the vision.</i>

03:50.956 --> 03:53.040
If I do not find an outfit
that portrays

03:53.125 --> 03:55.459
the paranoid near-eastern
mise-en-scéne, I'm screwed.

03:55.527 --> 03:56.911
<i>And I'm really worried
about Santana.</i>

03:56.995 --> 03:58.379
<i>She's got all the ambition,</i>

03:58.463 --> 04:00.164
<i>but she doesn't have
the focus.</i>

04:00.215 --> 04:01.465
Blaine's handsome
brother said it best:

04:01.533 --> 04:03.250
college is a waste of time.

04:03.335 --> 04:05.303
I just want to be famous,
plain and simple.

04:05.370 --> 04:06.587
Don't even care
how it happens.

04:06.672 --> 04:07.888
I just want everyone
to know my name.

04:07.973 --> 04:09.206
BRITTANY:
Cool.

04:09.257 --> 04:11.092
(bell ringing)

04:11.176 --> 04:12.543
<i>Honestly, I don't know
what to do.</i>

04:12.594 --> 04:14.312
I feel like I'm out of ideas.

04:14.379 --> 04:15.713
Oh, let's be honest, William.

04:15.764 --> 04:17.515
You've been out of ideas
since Madonna week.

04:17.565 --> 04:19.266
Why don't you
just embrace

04:19.351 --> 04:21.601
that lazy, horribly treacly
style of teaching

04:21.687 --> 04:23.053
and assign them a famous album?

04:23.105 --> 04:24.054
I did that last year.

04:24.106 --> 04:25.556
Yes, I remember, William.

04:25.607 --> 04:27.908
<i>And your Rumours week was
a resounding success</i>

04:27.993 --> 04:29.610
in that it seemed to solve

04:29.695 --> 04:32.896
everyone's problems
for about five minutes.

04:32.948 --> 04:35.199
Now I'm not talking about
just any album, William.

04:35.250 --> 04:38.902
How about the soundtrack
that defined a generation?

04:38.954 --> 04:39.754
Wait for it.

04:39.838 --> 04:41.922
<i>Saturday Night Fever.</i>

04:42.007 --> 04:43.124
I love that album.

04:43.208 --> 04:45.075
You bet your ass
you love that album.

04:45.127 --> 04:47.044
But there's just one problem--

04:47.095 --> 04:48.462
they hate disco.

04:48.547 --> 04:50.047
But they love swag.

04:50.098 --> 04:51.048
Jean jackets!

04:51.099 --> 04:52.266
Some mattresses!

04:52.351 --> 04:54.185
Dinner for two at Breadstix.

04:54.252 --> 04:55.136
Breadstix!

04:55.220 --> 04:57.087
(all cheer)

04:57.139 --> 04:59.523
Let's give 'em something
to fight over.

04:59.591 --> 05:00.808
Hmm.

05:00.892 --> 05:03.027
I'm thrilled you got into
Defiance College

05:03.094 --> 05:05.479
and Cleveland State,
but what about NYU?

05:05.564 --> 05:07.982
Kurt Hummel?
Mercedes Jones?

05:08.066 --> 05:10.368
I'm sorry to interrupt,
but I'm your biggest fan.

05:10.435 --> 05:12.436
I've been to every last one
of your performances,

05:12.487 --> 05:14.071
<i>except West Side Story.</i>

05:14.122 --> 05:16.874
I boycotted that one because
you two weren't Tony and Maria.

05:16.941 --> 05:18.909
Why, hello, kind sir.

05:18.960 --> 05:20.661
I don't believe
I caught your name.

05:20.746 --> 05:23.047
Wade Adams.
I go to Carmel High.

05:23.114 --> 05:25.466
And I'm in Vocal Adrenaline,
and I know we're supposed

05:25.550 --> 05:26.667
to be archenemies,

05:26.752 --> 05:29.470
but I swear,
I'm not here to spy.

05:29.554 --> 05:31.889
I want to ask your advice
about something.

05:31.956 --> 05:33.808
Our coach is
Jessie St. James.

05:33.892 --> 05:37.144
<i>The star of Vocal Adrenaline is
Vocal Adrenaline.</i>

05:37.229 --> 05:38.962
No one is special.
You're The Borg.

05:39.014 --> 05:40.648
You don't like it,
there's the fricking door.

05:40.732 --> 05:41.899
Am I clear,
Chunks McGriddle?

05:41.966 --> 05:42.933
Yes, sir.

05:42.984 --> 05:45.269
I can't hear you!

05:45.320 --> 05:46.437
Yes, sir.

05:46.488 --> 05:48.005
God, he's awful.

05:48.073 --> 05:52.443
He's nothing compared to the
kids at school... or my parents.

05:52.494 --> 05:54.662
Do you know how
I get through it?

05:54.746 --> 05:57.364
Ever since I was a kid,
I would play this game

05:57.449 --> 05:59.700
where I'd pretend I was
a different person,

05:59.785 --> 06:02.870
the person
that I dreamed of being...

06:02.954 --> 06:04.371
the real me.

06:04.456 --> 06:07.508
I even have a different name:

06:07.592 --> 06:09.376
"Unique."

06:09.461 --> 06:11.962
I got so nervous,
I almost didn't speak
to you guys today.

06:12.013 --> 06:14.998
But then I thought,
how would Unique do it?

06:15.050 --> 06:16.467
KURT:
What about NYU?

06:16.518 --> 06:18.636
Wait, wait.
Hold the thought.

06:18.687 --> 06:20.888
Someone with exquisite
taste is wearing...

06:20.972 --> 06:22.640
Joy. By Jean Patou.

06:23.725 --> 06:25.843
Kurt Hummel and Mercedes Jones,

06:25.894 --> 06:28.178
Unique worships
the red carpet you walk on.

06:28.230 --> 06:30.898
If you two had a love child,
it would be Unique.

06:30.982 --> 06:33.517
And Unique's grandparents would
be Andre Leon Talley

06:33.568 --> 06:36.854
and Beyoncé, because only
the best will do for Unique.

06:36.905 --> 06:38.689
Yes, fools,
it's real chinchilla!

06:38.740 --> 06:41.358
Unless you're planning on
splattering it with paint.

06:41.409 --> 06:43.494
Then it's fake.

06:43.545 --> 06:45.696
KURT: Unique sounds
like a really great person.

06:45.764 --> 06:47.131
I hope that,

06:47.198 --> 06:49.583
one day, you can build up
enough courage to be him.

06:49.668 --> 06:51.502
Actually, Unique's a "her."

06:51.553 --> 06:53.203
That's why I want
your advice.

06:53.255 --> 06:55.473
Our regionals are
this Saturday,

06:55.540 --> 06:58.542
and I want to go on stage
wearing a dress and heels.

06:58.593 --> 07:01.412
Because that's who I feel
like I am inside.

07:01.480 --> 07:02.229
Unique.

07:02.314 --> 07:03.848
Yes.

07:03.915 --> 07:05.566
What would you do?

07:07.152 --> 07:08.652
(bell ringing)

07:15.827 --> 07:17.194
Did someone steal our floor?

07:17.245 --> 07:19.914
Don't worry, we'll have it back
by the end of the week.

07:19.998 --> 07:21.832
In the meantime,
Sue has lent us her...

07:21.900 --> 07:23.751
...my very own personal,

07:23.835 --> 07:24.952
one-of-a-kind,
lit-from- within,

07:25.036 --> 07:27.571
shatterproof,
Plexiglas dance floor.

07:27.622 --> 07:29.072
Modeled, of course,
on the dance floor

07:29.124 --> 07:31.041
immortalized by a young,
musky John Travolta

07:31.092 --> 07:33.210
at the height
of his potency

07:33.261 --> 07:35.245
in the legendary
dansical

07:35.297 --> 07:36.597
<i>Saturday Night Fever.</i>

07:36.681 --> 07:38.415
Coach Sylvester, while we
applaud your proper use

07:38.466 --> 07:39.600
of the terminology,
we told Mr. Shue

07:39.684 --> 07:40.985
we do not support disco
in this room.

07:41.052 --> 07:41.969
Ah, but some of you do.

07:42.053 --> 07:43.487
So for this week's assignment,

07:43.555 --> 07:46.557
we are going back in time...

07:46.608 --> 07:48.776
to the songs of
"Saturday Night Fever."

07:48.860 --> 07:50.060
Come on, Mr. Shue.
That's, like,

07:50.111 --> 07:51.395
a record our parents listen to.

07:51.446 --> 07:53.531
That album, teen Solomon Grundy,

07:53.598 --> 07:56.317
is one of the best-selling
soundtracks of all time.

07:56.401 --> 07:58.903
Tony Manero's story is
your story.

07:58.954 --> 08:00.738
He's a guy who works
at a paint store,

08:00.789 --> 08:02.740
struggling to
figure out his life.

08:02.791 --> 08:04.542
And the only time
he feels sure about himself

08:04.609 --> 08:06.243
is when he's performing
on the dance floor.

08:06.294 --> 08:08.746
He has a dream.
To get out of his

08:08.797 --> 08:10.631
old neighborhood in Brooklyn
and get to New York City.

08:10.715 --> 08:13.300
And by the end of the movie,
that's what he's done.

08:13.385 --> 08:16.170
He's turned his
dream into a plan.

08:16.254 --> 08:18.088
So why the dance floor?

08:18.139 --> 08:19.890
Well, Porcelain,
because we're going to start

08:19.958 --> 08:21.258
with a dance-off.

08:21.309 --> 08:23.093
And the winner
will receive

08:23.144 --> 08:25.462
a replica of
John Travolta's iconic

08:25.513 --> 08:28.399
white polyester suit,
which I am having a cadre

08:28.466 --> 08:31.735
of expert Viennese
tailors painstakingly reproduce.

08:33.804 --> 08:35.739
("Calypso Breakdown" playing)

08:38.409 --> 08:39.994
Oh, my God, I need that suit!

08:40.078 --> 08:41.861
Oh, I bet that's worth
a lot of money.

08:41.947 --> 08:43.864
I would totally put
that suit on... eBay.

08:43.948 --> 08:45.032
So you just want us

08:45.116 --> 08:47.201
to start dancing
like Soul Train-style?

08:47.285 --> 08:49.203
Uh, no, actually, Sue
and I will start us off.

08:49.287 --> 08:50.871
We actually met
with Joe and Blaine beforehand.

08:50.956 --> 08:52.373
Just get up when you're ready.

08:52.457 --> 08:55.009
And everyone has to participate.
Everyone, Puck.

08:55.093 --> 08:56.010
All right, hit it.

